censusprov <- openxlsx::read.xlsx("censusProv.xlsx") %>%
  mutate(sigla_provincia = ifelse(is.na(sigla_provincia), "NA", sigla_provincia))
  
df <- read_json(path = "./dati-json/dpc-covid19-ita-province.json", simplifyVector = T) %>%
  filter(data != "data") %>%
  mutate(dataTime = as.POSIXct(data),
         data = as.Date(data),
         Regione = gsub("P.A. ", "", denominazione_regione)) %>%
  select(-denominazione_regione) %>%
  filter(sigla_provincia != "") %>%
  group_by(sigla_provincia) %>%
  #filter(sigla_provincia == "CR") %>%
  mutate(delta = totale_casi-lag(totale_casi),
         rateOfChange = delta/lag(totale_casi),
         logCasi = log(totale_casi)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  left_join(regSet, by = "Regione") %>%
  left_join(censusprov, by = "sigla_provincia") %>%
  mutate(casiOnPeop = totale_casi/Census)

popPerReg <- df %>%
  filter(data == max(data)) %>%
  group_by(Regione) %>%
  summarise(census = sum(Census),
            size = sum(Size),
            density = mean(Density),
            noCitis = sum(noCities))

maxDateTime = max(df$dataTime)

dfReg <- read_json(path = "./dati-json/dpc-covid19-ita-regioni.json", simplifyVector = T) %>%
  mutate(dataTime = as.POSIXct(data),
         data = as.Date(data),
         Regione = gsub("P.A. ", "", denominazione_regione)) %>%
  select(-denominazione_regione) %>%
  rename(deltaPositivi = nuovi_attualmente_positivi,
         Positivi = totale_attualmente_positivi) %>%
  left_join(popPerReg, by = "Regione") %>%
  arrange(data) %>%
  group_by(Regione) %>%
  mutate(deltaCasi = totale_casi-lag(totale_casi),
         ROC_casi = deltaCasi/lag(totale_casi),
         ROC_positivi = deltaPositivi/Positivi,
         logCasi = log(totale_casi),
         hospOnPositives = totale_ospedalizzati/Positivi,
         homeOnPositives = isolamento_domiciliare/Positivi,
         UCIonHosp = terapia_intensiva/totale_ospedalizzati,
         deathRate = deceduti/totale_casi,
         deathTest = deceduti/tamponi,
         recoverRate = dimessi_guariti/totale_casi,
         casiOnTests = totale_casi/tamponi,
         positiveOnCasi = Positivi/totale_casi,
         casiOnPop = totale_casi/census,
         tampOnPop = tamponi/census) %>%
  left_join(regSet, by = "Regione") %>%
  ungroup()

1.2 Model based on number of deads

dthRateHp <- 0.035
lag <- 16

The model relies on assuming the most reliable data is provided by the number of deads/date/region. Assuming a death rate of 3.5% and a lag between the detected infection and the actual death of 16 days, for each date/region you can derive the actual number of infected people over the total population of each region.

This can be charted as follows:

dfReg %>%
  arrange(data) %>%
  group_by(Regione) %>%
  mutate(leadDead = lead(deceduti, lag),
         hpCasi = leadDead/dthRateHp,
         hpCasiOnCasi = hpCasi/totale_casi) %>%
  filter(!is.infinite(hpCasiOnCasi), !is.na(hpCasiOnCasi), !is.nan(hpCasiOnCasi),
         data > as.Date("2020-02-27"),
         !(Regione  %in% c("Bolzano", "Trento"))) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x= data, y = hpCasiOnCasi, color = Regione)) +
  geom_line() +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(title = "Infected multiplier by date/region",
       subtitle = paste0("Death rate: ", format(dthRateHp* 100), "%, lag: ", lag, " days"),
       caption = paste("SOURCE: DPC data as of", format(maxDateTime, "%d-%h %H:%M")),
       x= "",
       y = "Multiplier")

The resulting dataset can then be analysed.

test <- dfReg %>%
  arrange(data) %>%

  ungroup()

The current regression model hasn’t been optimized and just relies on a reasonable assumption that the number of people infected is linked to the percentage of people being tested and the broad location.

top10 <- dfReg %>%
    filter(data == max(data),
           !(Regione %in% c("Bolzano", "Trento"))) %>%
    left_join(test[test$data == max(test$data), c("Regione", "hpCasiOnCasi")], by= "Regione") %>%
    mutate(hpCasi = hpCasiOnCasi * totale_casi,
           percPopHp = hpCasi/census,
           percPop = totale_casi/census) %>%

    select(Regione, deceduti, totale_casi, hpCasiOnCasi, hpCasi, census, percPopHp, percPop) %>%

2 Charting the death path

2.1 Tree-based model

The model implemented is the Generalized Boosted Regression Model (GBM)

This is a “black-box” style model which is very useful for prediction and somewhat useful for inference (returning the set of the most important variables thrown at it).

The attempt is to fit the daily change in the death number (DDeads variable).

modelSet <- dfReg %>%
  select(data, ricov = ricoverati_con_sintomi, ICU = terapia_intensiva,
         homeBound = isolamento_domiciliare, currentPositives = Positivi,
         discharged = dimessi_guariti, deads = deceduti, totalInfected = totale_casi,
         tests = tamponi, Region = Regione, Pop = census, RegSize = size,
         RegAvgDens = density, MainArea = class) %>%
  mutate(MainArea = as.factor(MainArea),
         Region = as.factor(Region),
         days = as.numeric(data-min(data))) %>%
  select(-data) %>%
  arrange(days) %>%
  group_by(Region) %>%
  mutate(DDeads = deads-lag(deads)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  filter(!is.na(DDeads)) %>%
  select(-c(currentPositives, ricov, totalInfected, deads))

is.fact <- sapply(modelSet, is.factor)
is.num <- sapply(modelSet, is.numeric)

Variables: 2 are factors and 9 are numeric.

dependentVariable <- "DDeads"

depVar <- modelSet[, dependentVariable]
num.var <- modelSet[, !(names(modelSet) %in% dependentVariable) & is.num]
fact.var <- modelSet[, is.fact]

correlation <- cor(num.var)

highCorr <- findCorrelation(correlation, cutoff = .80)
highCorrNames <- names(num.var[, highCorr])
corrplot(correlation, type= "lower", order = "hclust")

Highly correlated variables: ICU,tests,homeBound Ideally you would get rid of them to avoid multicollnearity (but this is a tree-based model)

Transforming factors into dummy variable (with all cases - tree model)

trnsFact <- dummyVars(~., data=fact.var, fullRank = F)
factData <- predict(trnsFact, fact.var)

fullSet_pp <- cbind(factData, num.var, depVar)

Cross-validation using GBM/Caret

set.seed(1)
inTraining <- createDataPartition(fullSet_pp[, dependentVariable], p = 2/3, list = FALSE)
train <- fullSet_pp[inTraining,]
test <- fullSet_pp[-inTraining,]

Grid <-  expand.grid(shrinkage = 0.1, #seq(0.0075, 0.01, by=0.0025),
                     n.trees = seq(100, 300, by= 100),
                     n.minobsinnode = seq(1, 2, by = 1),
                     interaction.depth = seq(1, 2, by = 1))

control <- trainControl(method="cv", number=10)

rf.fit <- train(DDeads ~., data = train,
                tuneGrid = Grid,
                method = "gbm",
                trControl = control,
                verbose = F)

RMSEtrn <- sqrt(mean((train[, dependentVariable]-predict(rf.fit, train))^2))
RMSEtst <- sqrt(mean((test[, dependentVariable]-predict(rf.fit, test))^2))

RMSE train: 6.30387802121823 and RMSE test: 20.9516986308673

2.2 Lasso model

Same exercise using a more traditional regression model based on the lasso technique (shrinking the number of variables via a penalty applied to the weakest regressors). This model is less effective (typically) but it allows for easier inference.

x_vars <- model.matrix(DDeads ~. , modelSet)
y_var <- modelSet$DDeads

lambda_seq <- 10^seq(0, -1, by = -.1)
set.seed(86)
train = sample(1:nrow(x_vars), nrow(x_vars) * 2 / 3)
test = setdiff(1:nrow(x_vars), train)

cv_output <- cv.glmnet(x_vars[train,], y_var[train], 
                       alpha = 1, lambda = lambda_seq)

s <- cv_output$lambda.min

coeff <- data.frame(
  feature=rownames(coef(cv_output, s=s))[which(coef(cv_output, s=s) != 0)],
  coeficient=coef(cv_output, s=s)[which(coef(cv_output, s=s) != 0)]
)
print(coeff)
##                feature   coeficient
## 1          (Intercept) -0.607064159
## 2                  ICU  0.117891026
## 3            homeBound  0.001037276
## 4           discharged  0.038216327
## 5 RegionEmilia Romagna 11.767356499
## 6         RegionVeneto -3.157306460
lasso_best <- glmnet(x_vars[train,], y_var[train], alpha = 1, lambda = s)

predtrain <- data.frame(pred = as.vector(predict(lasso_best, s = s, newx = x_vars[train,])),
                        act = y_var[train],
                        set = "Train",
                        stringsAsFactors = F)
RMSEtrain <- sqrt(mean((predtrain$pred-y_var[train])^2, na.rm = T))

predtest <- data.frame(pred = as.vector(predict(lasso_best, s = s, newx = x_vars[test,])),
                       act = y_var[test],
                       set = "Test",
                       stringsAsFactors = F)

RMSEtest <- sqrt(mean((predtest$pred-y_var[test])^2, na.rm = T))
